# Next.js Frontend Rules — Luis Alarcon Portfolio

## App Router File Structure

Follow the Next.js 14+ App Router conventions strictly:

```
frontend/
├── app/
│   ├── layout.tsx          # Root layout — wraps all pages, mounts AuthContext
│   ├── page.tsx            # Home page — Hero + Projects + About + Contact
│   ├── loading.tsx         # Root loading UI (Suspense boundary)
│   ├── error.tsx           # Root error boundary
│   └── globals.css
├── components/
│   ├── ui/                 # Primitive, stateless UI components
│   ├── hero/
│   ├── projects/
│   ├── about/
│   └── contact/
├── lib/
│   └── api.ts              # ← ALL backend API calls live here, nowhere else
├── context/
│   └── auth-context.tsx    # JWT auth context (even if auth is not v1 scope)
├── types/
│   └── index.ts            # All shared TypeScript types and interfaces
└── hooks/
    └── use-repositories.ts # Example data-fetching hook
```

- Use `page.tsx`, `layout.tsx`, `loading.tsx`, `error.tsx` naming — no deviations.
- Do not use the `pages/` directory. App Router only.
- Co-locate component files with their section folder, not in a flat `/components` root dump.
- Server Components are the default. Mark client components explicitly with `"use client"` only when needed (interactivity, hooks, browser APIs).

---

## No Mock Data — Ever

**Never use hardcoded mock data, static JSON fixtures, or placeholder arrays in any component or hook.**

- Every data value rendered in the UI must come from a real API response originating from the FastAPI backend.
- The backend proxies GitHub API calls and handles caching against Postgres — the frontend does not call `api.github.com` directly.
- If the backend is unavailable during development, fix the backend. Do not patch the frontend with fake data.
- Test components with the real dev backend running via `docker-compose up`.

```typescript
// ❌ NEVER do this
const repos = [
  { id: 1, name: "fake-repo", description: "placeholder" }
];

// ✅ Always do this
const { data: repos, isLoading, error } = useRepositories();
```

---

## All API Calls Go Through `/lib/api.ts`

**`/lib/api.ts` is the single source of truth for all HTTP communication with the backend.**

- No `fetch()` calls outside of `/lib/api.ts`.
- No `axios` instances defined outside of `/lib/api.ts`.
- No inline URLs or hardcoded `localhost:8000` strings in components or hooks.
- Hooks in `/hooks/` call functions exported from `/lib/api.ts`. Components call hooks.

```typescript
// lib/api.ts — canonical shape

const API_BASE_URL = process.env.NEXT_PUBLIC_API_URL ?? "http://localhost:8000";

async function apiFetch<T>(path: string, options?: RequestInit): Promise<T> {
  const res = await fetch(`${API_BASE_URL}${path}`, {
    ...options,
    headers: {
      "Content-Type": "application/json",
      ...options?.headers,
    },
  });

  if (!res.ok) {
    throw new Error(`API error ${res.status}: ${path}`);
  }

  return res.json() as Promise<T>;
}

export async function getRepositories(): Promise<Repository[]> {
  return apiFetch<Repository[]>("/api/repositories");
}

export async function getRepository(name: string): Promise<Repository> {
  return apiFetch<Repository>(`/api/repositories/${name}`);
}
```

- All functions in `api.ts` must be explicitly typed — return types are never inferred as `any`.
- Add new API functions here as new backend endpoints are added. Never inline them at the call site.

---

## Loading and Error States Required on Every Fetch

**Every component or page that fetches data must handle three states: loading, error, and success. No exceptions.**

This applies even though v1 targets the happy path. The structure must be in place.

```typescript
// hooks/use-repositories.ts
"use client";

import { useEffect, useState } from "react";
import { getRepositories } from "@/lib/api";
import type { Repository } from "@/types";

interface UseRepositoriesResult {
  data: Repository[] | null;
  isLoading: boolean;
  error: string | null;
}

export function useRepositories(): UseRepositoriesResult {
  const [data, setData] = useState<Repository[] | null>(null);
  const [isLoading, setIsLoading] = useState(true);
  const [error, setError] = useState<string | null>(null);

  useEffect(() => {
    let cancelled = false;

    async function load() {
      try {
        setIsLoading(true);
        setError(null);
        const repos = await getRepositories();
        if (!cancelled) setData(repos);
      } catch (err) {
        if (!cancelled) setError(err instanceof Error ? err.message : "Failed to load repositories");
      } finally {
        if (!cancelled) setIsLoading(false);
      }
    }

    load();
    return () => { cancelled = true; };
  }, []);

  return { data, isLoading, error };
}
```

```tsx
// components/projects/projects-grid.tsx
"use client";

import { useRepositories } from "@/hooks/use-repositories";

export function ProjectsGrid() {
  const { data: repos, isLoading, error } = useRepositories();

  // ✅ Loading state — required
  if (isLoading) {
    return <ProjectsGridSkeleton />;
  }

  // ✅ Error state — required
  if (error) {
    return (
      <p className="text-red-500 text-sm">
        Could not load repositories. {error}
      </p>
    );
  }

  // ✅ Success state
  return (
    <div className="grid grid-cols-1 md:grid-cols-2 lg:grid-cols-3 gap-4">
      {repos?.map((repo) => (
        <ProjectCard key={repo.id} repo={repo} />
      ))}
    </div>
  );
}
```

- Use skeleton components for loading states — not spinners alone, not `"Loading..."` text.
- Error messages must be human-readable. Include the raw error only in development.
- Never render `null` silently when a fetch fails — always surface something to the user.

