## TypeScript Strict Mode — No `any` Types

`tsconfig.json` must have strict mode enabled:

```json
{
  "compilerOptions": {
    "strict": true,
    "noImplicitAny": true,
    "strictNullChecks": true,
    "noUncheckedIndexedAccess": true
  }
}
```

**Rules:**

- `any` is banned. Use `unknown` for values of indeterminate type, then narrow explicitly.
- All function parameters and return types must be explicitly annotated or clearly inferrable — no implicit `any` from missing types.
- All shared types live in `/types/index.ts`. Do not define one-off inline types in component files.
- API response shapes must be typed before use — define the type in `/types/index.ts`, pass it as the generic to `apiFetch<T>`.

```typescript
// types/index.ts

export interface Repository {
  id: number;
  name: string;
  description: string | null;
  html_url: string;
  language: string | null;
  topics: string[];
  stargazers_count: number;
  updated_at: string;
  pushed_at: string;
}
```

```typescript
// ❌ NEVER
const data: any = await res.json();

// ✅ Correct
const data: Repository[] = await apiFetch<Repository[]>("/api/repositories");
```

- Use `type` for unions and utility types. Use `interface` for object shapes and API contracts.
- ESLint rule `@typescript-eslint/no-explicit-any` must be set to `"error"`.

